source.4d2cc5cc:
Let's analyze in detail the chart above.

First of all, it is worth remembering that the curves plotted above represent the daily variation of reported and diagnosed cases (i.e. today there were 200 cases more than yesterday, etc.). They are NOT infections, as those must have happened a number of days before.

The accepted covid-19 incubation period is **2 to 14 days**, with an average of 5 days and some cases diagnosed even after 21 days of infection. 

During the days before the lock downs (left of the shadowed areas), covid-19 was expanding with minimum control and infections were happening everywhere: in the office, at the gym, in the club, at the library, in a funeral!

From the moment lock downs were enforced, the virus transmission was interrupted. However, those infected during the days before will begin to feel symptoms and report them.

Confronted with the evidence of an uncontrolled expansion, containement measures were finally taken:

- Italy enforced a full lock down on March 9th, and the curve peaked 12 days later with a daily variation of about 6.5K. Its high growth rate window spans from March 9th through to March 21st.

- Spain applied a lock-down on the 14th, and the curve reached the peak at almost 10K on March 25th, that is 11 days later. Spain's high growth rate window run then from March 14th through to March 25th.

We can shift the above **high growth windows** areas back by the number of incubation days and estimate that way the **high infection windows**.

Let's do that for Italy and Spain separately.

Sources:

https://www.who.int/health-topics/coronavirus#tab=tab_3

https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/symptoms-testing/symptoms.html
source.ea48c7bc:
Here we go. We now have all five countries curves aligned, each of them shifted a number of days:

- Spain and Germany shifted 6 days back
- France shifted 10 days
- UK shifted 16 days back

This is equivalent to a hypothetical situation in which all countries would have experienced the outbreak at the same time. By doing this, we can easily compare how fast the virus has expanded in each country.

We can see how Italy, UK and Germany seem to have a very similar evolution up to approx. 120K, with France somewhat adhering to that trend but with higher volatility.

Spain instead experienced a faster growth from well earlier, reaching also higher numbers of cases than its neighbours. But as indicated before, the Spanish authorities implemented a strict lock-down on March the 14th when the number of cases was 6391.Comparing with Italy, which enforced the lock-down on March 9th with 9172 cases, or with France which did so on March 17th with 7652, Spain does not seem to have delayed the introduction of confinement meaures beyond the reasonable. 

So what made the Spanish infections grow so rapidly then???

What follows now is a **timeline of covid-19** events, to set a context.

**10 January 2020**

WHO issued a comprehensive package of technical guidance online with advice to all countries on how to detect, test and manage potential cases, based on what was known about the virus at the time. This guidance was shared with WHO's regional emergency directors to share with WHO representatives in countries. 

**22 January 2020**

WHO mission to China issued a statement saying that there was evidence of human-to-human transmission in Wuhan but more investigation was needed to understand the full extent of transmission.

**22 - 23 January 2020**

WHO Director convened an Emergency Committee (EC) under the International Health Regulations (IHR 2005) to assess whether the outbreak constituted a public health emergency of international concern. The independent members from around the world could not reach a consensus based on the evidence available at the time and asked to reconvene within 10 days after receiving more information.

**30 January 2020**

WHO Director reconvened the Emergency Committee (EC) earlier than the 10-day period and only two days after the first reports of limited human-to-human transmission were reported outside China. This time, the EC reached consensus and advised the Director that the outbreak constituted a **Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC)**. The Director accepted the recommendation and declared the novel coronavirus outbreak (2019-nCoV) a PHEIC. WHO’s situation report for 30 January reported 7818 total confirmed cases worldwide, with the majority of these in China, and 82 cases reported in 18 countries outside China. WHO gave a **risk assessment of very high for China, and high at the global level**.

**11 February 2020**

WHO communicated the official name of **COVID-19** for the virus and mandated that the name of the disease could not refer to a geographical location, an animal, an individual or group of people. It also needed to relate to the disease and be pronounceable, hoping that this choice will help guard against the use of other names that might be inaccurate or stigmatizing.

**12 February 2020**

The GSMA cancels the Mobile World Congress (MWC) Barcelona 2020 due to the global concern regarding the covid-19 outbreak. By that time, Amazon, Deutsche Telekom, Ericsson, Facebook, HMD, Intel, LG, Nokia, NTT Docomo, Sony and Sprint had already cancelled their attendance.

**17 February 2020**

Based on lessons from H1N1 and Ebola, WHO outlined planning guidance for organizers of mass gatherings and also issued advice on how to detect and take care of ill travellers, in light of the COVID-19 outbreak.

**21 February 2020**

WHO Director warns that the window of opportunity to contain the outbreak is “narrowing” and that the international community needs to act quickly, including through financing.

**2 March 2020**

Speaking at the COVID-19 media briefing, WHO Director communicated that the virus was capable of **community transmission** but could be contained with the right measures, emphasizing “there’s no choice but to act now”. 

**3 March 2020**

Germany cancels the International Woman's Day public event planned for March 5th, along with 130 events which were expected to be attended by 6000 to 7000 participants.

**5 March 2020**

Speaking at the COVID-19 media briefing, WHO Director manifested that the COVID-19 epidemic "can be pushed back, but only with a collective coordinated and comprehensive approach that engages the entire machinery of government”. Through a Twitter note, WHO added: **"We are concerned that in some countries the level of political commitment and the actions that demonstrate that commitment do not match the level of the threat we all face"** 

Also on March 5th, the Paris Marathon due to take place on April 5th was cancelled and postponed to October due to concerns of covid-19 contagions.

**7 March 2020** 

The number of infections of covid-19 in the world reached **100K cases**. Marking this sombre moment, WHO reminded all countries and communities that the spread of this virus could be significantly slowed down or even reversed through the implementation of robust containment and control activities, and that **allowing uncontrolled spread should not be a choice of any government**.

**8 March 2020** 

International Woman's Day, the reivindicative celebration of feminist character goes ahead in many countries. In Spain, an estimated 600K people gathered together in the streets, with 120K just in Madrid, one of the most severely hit provinces.

**11 March 2020**

WHO declared COVID-19 a **pandemic**.

**13 March 2020**

Europe became the world's epicenter of the pandemic, overtaking the rest of the world (excluded China) in reported cases and deaths.

## Analysis of the daily variation of cases (individual plots)

The daily variation of cases can be computed by substracting the number of cases on day t-1 from the number of cases on day t. 

This is no more than the first derivative of the cummulative confirmed cases variable, and represents its **rate of grotwh**. 

This is a helpful variable that eliminates the growing trend information from the confirmed cases series, and results useful to predict the end of the pandemic expansion, which can be considered to be under control when this variable reaches and remains zero, as no new cases will be added from that moment.

source.fa5eabf1:
Ignoring all available evidence and repeated warnings from WHO, during the weekend of March 7th - 8th, a number of mass events took place in Spain.

Just to mention a few of the largest ones:

- Betis - Real Madrid football match in Sevilla, bringing together more than 60K supporters.
- Political gathering of the Spanish right-wing political party (Vox) in Vistalegre, where 9K people got together, and at least two politicians got infected.
- Atletico de Madrid - Sevilla football match in Madrid on March 7th, also bringing together around 60K supporters.
- And most notably, the International Woman's Day on March the 8th, during which more than 600K people gathered together in the streets (with 120K just in Madrid and around 50K in Barcelona). Several politicians from the governing left-wing party, who had actively promoted attendance to this event in the previous days, got infected too. 

People infected on those days continued propagating the virus over the following days and until March 14th when the lock-down came into effect.

There can not be much questioning about the fact that these events acted as an **infections amplifier**, contributing to Spain becoming one of the most infected countries.

## How Spain ended up leading the number of covid-19 infections

---

Last updated: 29/05/2020

This notebook performs a comparative analysis of the covid-19 pandemic expansion across a number of countries, from the 22nd of January through to the end of May, particulaly covering the period and geography beyond China's outbreak and just as the bulk of the infections was movint to the Americas.  

I will also conduct an investigation around the special circumstances surrounding one of the hardest hit countries, that is Spain.

The ten countries included in this research work are:

- Spain, Italy, France, Germany and UK (the European set)
- Australia, Brazil, Canada, Iran and USA (the rest of the world set)

Data can be obtained from the COVID-19 Data Repository by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University:

https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19
